<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-08-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-08-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="445" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d445">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Lord Lyons</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-08-05"><hi rend="italic">August</hi> 5, 1864.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">My Lord</hi>: Referring to your note of the 11th of
                            last month, relative to the appeal in the case of the steamer Pearl, I
                            have the honor to inform your lordship, <pb facs="0689" n="669" xml:id="pg_669"/> in reply, that the Attorney General will examine
                            the facts, with a view to enable me to decide upon the propriety of
                            dismissing the appeal, as soon as he shall have received the proper
                            record.</p>
                        <p>I have the honor to be, with high consideration, my lord, your obedient
                            servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p>Right Hon. <hi rend="smallcaps">Lord Lyons.</hi>
                                <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>